  <span class="cite"><u>In re Smith</u>, 2000-2627 (La. 11/28/00, <a href="../SC/2000-11-27_2000-2627.htm">___ So. 2d
  ____</a>, 2000 WL 1752214</span>.</p>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a href="#_ednref5" name="_edn5" class="fn" id="_edn5">[v]</a> <i>See</i>
  <span class="cite"><u>In re Kennedy</u>, 542 A.2d 1225 (D.C. 1988)</span>. (Court held that continuing to practice
  law while suspended due to nonpayment of bar membership fees and violation of disciplinary rule prohibiting attorney
  from engaging in conduct involving dishonesty, fraud, deceit or misrepresentation arising from attorney's personal
  financial affairs, as opposed to his representation of a client, warrants suspension from practice of law for ninety
  days.)</p>
  <hr />

  <div id="dissentLeake">
    <p class="headingstyle">Docket No. 00-DB-148</p>

    <p class="headingstyle">Ronald Hammock</p>

    <p class="headingstyle">Dissent :</p>

    <p class="Bodycopy">The proposed sanction is a public reprimand. The violation is practicing law while ineligible
    for non-payment of Bar dues and disciplinary assessments.</p>

    <p class="Bodycopy">Respondent became ineligible to practice as of November 1, 1993. A telephone call to the LSBA
    confirms that he is <u>still ineligible</u>.</p>

    <p class="Bodycopy">His acceptance of a curatorship appointment can only be a flagrant, intentional violation.
    Anyone who remains ineligible for over seven years is either not serious about his license or is seriously
    contemptuous of the rules.</p>

    <p class="Bodycopy">Any lawyer who has not done MCLE for over seven years (the only possible assumption) is prima
    facie incompetent.</p>

    <p class="Bodycopy">I dissent from the proposed consent discipline; it is too lenient; a serious suspension with
    following probation is in order.</p>

    <p class="Bodycopy"> New Orleans, May 21, 2001.</p>

    <p class="Bodycopy">Robert E. Leake, Jr.</p>
